        t.addLesson(new Lesson("3. Chaining ratios together", "<p>Sometimes you're told a : b and b : c separately and must find a : c. The trick is to make the shared letter (b) the <strong>same number</strong> in both.</p>" + Doc.example("a : b = 2 : 3 and b : c = 4 : 5. Find a : c.", "b is 3 in the first and 4 in the second. Make both 12 (the LCM): scale the first by 4 \u2192 8 : 12, and the second by 3 \u2192 12 : 15. Now b matches, so a : b : c = 8 : 12 : 15, giving <strong>a : c = 8 : 15</strong>.") + Doc.analogy("It's like swapping currencies: if 1 apple = 3 coins and 4 coins = 5 berries, you make the \u2018coins\u2019 match on both sides before comparing apples to berries.") + Doc.tip("Make the common term equal to the LCM of its two values \u2014 it keeps the numbers whole and small.") + Doc.recap("To chain ratios, scale them so the shared term is identical, then read off the combined ratio."), 3));
        t.addLesson(new Lesson("4. Proportion: direct vs inverse", "<p>A <strong>proportion</strong> says two ratios are equal, e.g. a/b = c/d. From it we get the famous <strong>cross-multiplication</strong>:</p>" + Doc.formula("a/b = c/d &nbsp; \u27f9 &nbsp; a \u00d7 d = b \u00d7 c") + "<p>Use cross-multiplication only when two complete ratios are equal. It is a tool for solving unknowns, not for comparing unrelated numbers.</p><h4>Direct proportion \u2014 grow together</h4><p>When one amount doubles, the other doubles too. More items cost more money.</p>" + Doc.analogy("If 1 chocolate costs 20, then 3 chocolates cost 60. Cost goes up <em>in step</em> with quantity \u2014 that's direct proportion.") + Doc.formula("Direct: y = k \u00d7 x &nbsp; (the ratio y/x stays constant)") + Doc.example("Fuel and distance (constant mileage)", "If a bike gives 40 km per litre, then 3 litres gives 120 km and 5 litres gives 200 km. Distance grows directly with litres.") + "<h4>Inverse proportion \u2014 see-saw</h4><p>When one amount goes up, the other goes <em>down</em>, so their product stays the same.</p>" + Doc.analogy("More workers finish a job faster. If you double the workers, the time halves \u2014 like a see-saw: one side up, the other down.") + Doc.formula("Inverse: x \u00d7 y = k &nbsp; (the product stays constant)") + Doc.example("Speed-time with fixed distance", "If a route takes 4 hours at 60 km/h, then at 80 km/h time becomes 3 hours because speed\u00d7time is fixed (240).") + Doc.example("12 workers build a wall in 10 days. How long for 8 workers?", "Work is fixed, so workers \u00d7 days is constant: 12\u00d710 = 120. With 8 workers: days = 120 \u00f7 8 = <strong>15 days</strong> (fewer workers \u2192 more time).") + "<h4>Fast decision test</h4>" + Doc.steps("Ask: if input increases, should output increase (direct) or decrease (inverse)?", "For direct, keep ratio y/x constant. For inverse, keep product xy constant.", "After solving, do a reason check: does the answer move in the expected direction?") + Doc.warn("Decide direct or inverse <em>before</em> calculating. Ask: \u201cif this goes up, should the other go up (direct) or down (inverse)?\u201d") + Doc.recap("Proportion = equal ratios (cross-multiply). Direct: ratio constant. Inverse: product constant."), 4));
        t.addLesson(new Lesson("5. Partnership: sharing profit fairly", "<p>When friends start a business together, the profit is shared <strong>in the ratio of how much each one contributes</strong>. If they invest for different lengths of time, we use <em>money &times; time</em>.</p>" + Doc.analogy("Think of a shared lemonade stand: if you put in twice as much money as your friend, you should get twice the profit. Fair shares follow the ratio of contributions.") + "<h4>Simple case (same time period)</h4><p>Profit is split in the ratio of the amounts invested.</p>" + Doc.example("A invests 3000, B invests 2000, profit is 1000", "Ratio = 3000 : 2000 = 3 : 2 (5 parts). One part = 1000 \u00f7 5 = 200. A gets 3\u00d7200 = <strong>600</strong>, B gets 2\u00d7200 = <strong>400</strong>.") + "<h4>Different time periods</h4>" + Doc.formula("share ratio = (money\u2081 \u00d7 months\u2081) : (money\u2082 \u00d7 months\u2082)") + Doc.tip("Always reduce the contribution ratio first \u2014 smaller numbers make the share-out easier.") + Doc.recap("Profit is divided in the ratio of contributions; with unequal time, use money \u00d7 time."), 5));
